ParaMIDI represents music with data, not code!

(piano, c, d, e)
/piano c d e

You can change the instrument any time.

(piano, c, d, organ, d, c)
/piano c d /organ d c

You can change attributes such as note length.

(piano, c, (length: 1/2), d, e)
/piano c /length 1/2 d e

Scope works just like you'd expect.

(piano, c, ((length: 1/2), d), e)
/piano c /length 1/2 d /length 1/4 e

Or more tersely...

(piano, c, (1/2, d), e)
/piano c 1/2 d 1/4 e

You can change the octave as well.

(piano, c, d-1, e)
/piano c d-1 e

To make chords, put notes in a set.

(piano, 1/2, {a, cx, e})
/piano 1/2 a,c#,e

Chords can span multiple octaves.

(piano, 1/2, {-d, d, +d, fx})
/piano 1/2 d-,d,d+,f#

With only these building blocks, you can make the following.

(flute, 1/8, {d,-a,-d}, e, 1/4, fx, a, 1/8, fx, 1/4, e, 1/2, {d,-a,-d})
/flute /8 d,a-,d- e /4 f# a /8 f# /4 e /2 d,a-,d-

(piano,
  1/4, c, 1/2, {f,-f}, 1/8, a, f, 1/2, {a,-f},
  1/4, f, 1/2, {f,-a}, 1/4, d, 1/2, {c,-f},
  harmonica,
  1/4, c, 1/2, {f,-f}, 1/8, a, f, 1/2, {a,-f},
  1/8, g, a, 1/2, {-c,+c},
  violin,
  1/4, a, 1/2, {-f,+c}, 1/8, a, f, 1/2, {a,-f},
  1/4, g, 1/2, {f,-a}, 1/4, d, 1/2, {c,-f},
  baritone_sax,
  1/4, c, 1/2, {f,-f}, 1/8, a, f, 1/2, {a,-c},
  1/4, g, 1, {f,-f})
/piano c /2 f,f- /8 a f /2 a,f- /4 g /2 f,a- /4 d /2 c,f- /harmonica 1/4 c /2 f,f- /8 a f /2 a,f- /8 g a /2 c-,c+ /violin 1/4 a /2 f-,c+ /8 a f /2 a,f- /4 g /2 f,a- /4 d /2 c,f- /baritone-sax 1/4 c /2 f,f- /8 a f /2 a,c- /4 g 1 f,f-

Scores can also be written with Nim's JSON module.
This is useful if you need to generate scores at runtime.

%*["flute",
   1/8, [{"mode":"concurrent"},"d","a-","d-"],
   "e", 1/4, "f#", "a", 1/8, "f#", 1/4, "e",
   1/2, [{"mode":"concurrent"},"d","a-","d-"]]

One obvious use for paraMIDI is games.
Most game developers have to use external tools for this.
With paraMIDI your music is part of your game's source code.
You can even use gameplay to affect the music dynamically.

Check out some longer examples:
https://github.com/paranim/paramidi/tree/master/examples

To get started, clone the starter project:
https://github.com/paranim/paramidi_starter


